<TITLE> Govt to form national human rights commission: CA </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 24 (bdnews24.com)  Chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed Wednesday said his government would form a national human rights commission to investigate all forms of human rights abuses. "We will soon form the national human rights commission with powers to investigate all forms of human rights abusesbe it by governmental agencies, political parties or private citizens," he said at a conference marking the 62nd founding anniversary of the United Nations. The interim government head said his administration would not allow a 'government of the money, by the money and for the money' to be installed. "My government is tirelessly working for a government which will truly be of the people, by the people and for the people," Fakhruddin said. "We no longer want to endure governments of the money, by the money and for the money," the chief adviser said. The UN office in Dhaka organised the conference at the Bangladesh-China Friendship Conference Centre. UN resident coordinator Renata Dessallien in her speech lauded Bangladesh's active role in the UN system. She read out a message of the UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-Moon on the anniversary of 192-member world body. The UN was established on Oct 24, 1945 and Bangladesh joined it as the 136th member country on Sept 17, 1974. Foreign adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury and former foreign minister Dr Kamal Hossain were among those who attended the conference. bdnews
